'''''Lombard RAC Rally''''' is a 1988 [[Rallying|rally]] [[video game]] developed by [[Red Rat Software]] and published by [[Mandarin Software]] (an imprint of [[Europress]]).

The game was based on the same rally (under the earlier sponsors' names) as the later ''Network Q RAC Rally'' games, and was the first of a [[Rally Championship (series)|series of related games]] published by Europress. It was released for the [[Atari ST]],<ref name='atarimania-16'>{{cite web|url=http://www.atarimania.com/game-atari-st-lombard-rac-rally_22603.html|title=Atari ST Lombard RAC Rally: scans, dump, download, screenshots, ads, videos, catalog, instructions, roms|website=Atarimania.com|accessdate=31 December 2018}}</ref> [[Amiga]]<ref name='lemonamiga'>{{cite web|url=http://www.lemonamiga.com/?game_id=1581|title=Lombard RAC Rally - Lemon Amiga|website=Lemonamiga.com|accessdate=31 December 2018}}</ref> and [[MS-DOS]]<ref name='mobygames'>{{cite web|url=https://www.mobygames.com/game/lombard-rac-rally/screenshots|title=Lombard RAC Rally (1988) screenshots|website=MobyGames.com|accessdate=31 December 2018}}</ref> formats.

The game prominently features an animated driver, seen from behind moving the steering wheel, with the road seen through the car's windscreen.

The game cover art features [[Jimmy McRae]]'s [[Ford Sierra RS Cosworth]] from 1987.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gettyimages.ie/detail/news-photo/jimmy-mcrae-of-great-britain-driving-a-ford-sierra-as-he-news-photo/130234553|title = Jimmy McRae of Great Britain driving a Ford Sierra as he races}}</ref>

Inspiration for the game came to Charles Partington and Harry Nadler (of RedRat Software) one lunch time when they were watching Lombard RAC Rally coverage on TV at the Top Cat Tavern (Manchester Corn Exchange/Hanging Ditch), which was located just around the corner from RedRat's offices. Charles and Harry had not previously seen rally coverage from an 'in-car' perspective and commented to each other that "we have to make a game out of this".

